Q. what is quese and jobs in laravell
A. Queues and Jobs are used to handle time-consuming tasks in the background, so your application stays fast and responsive.
	without queue : Mail::to($user)->send(new WelcomeMail());
	with queue : Mail::to($user)->queue(new WelcomeMail());
	
	What is a Job?
👉 A Job is a class that represents a task to be executed in the queue.
	Example Job
	php artisan make:job SendEmailJob
	
	class SendEmailJob implements ShouldQueue
	{
		public function handle()
		{
			// heavy task
			Mail::to($this->user)->send(new WelcomeMail());
		}
	}
	SendEmailJob::dispatch($user);
	
Q. what is laravel collections?
A. Collections are one of the most powerful and elegant features—especially for handling arrays and data sets.
	Laravel Collections = A wrapper around arrays that provides powerful methods to manipulate data easily and fluently
	
	Why use Collections?
	Instead of writing complex loops (foreach, if), you can write clean, readable, chainable code.

	Without Collection : 
	$numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
	$result = [];

	foreach ($numbers as $num) {
		if ($num % 2 == 0) {
			$result[] = $num * 2;
		}
	}
	
	With Collection : 
	$numbers = collect([1, 2, 3, 4, 5]);

	$result = $numbers
		->filter(fn($n) => $n % 2 == 0)
		->map(fn($n) => $n * 2);
		
	Common Methods
	filter() : $users->filter(fn($user) => $user->age > 18);
	map()	: $users->map(fn($user) => $user->name);
	where()	: $users->where('status', 'active');
	pluck()	: $users->pluck('email');
	sort()	: $users->sortBy('name');
	first()	; $users->first();
	
	Chaining (Best Feature)
	$emails = User::all()
    ->where('status', 'active')
    ->pluck('email')
    ->sort();
	
	Difference from array : 
	Feature				Array			Collection
	Methods				❌ Limited		✅ Rich methods
	Readability			❌ Low			✅ High
	Chaining			❌ No			✅ Yes
	Functional style	❌ No			✅ Yes
	
